[8] Serbia: measles outbreak declared over
Date: Sun 1 Sep 2019
From: Jovicic Aleksandar <jovicic.aleksandar@gmail.com> [edited]


The Institute of Public Health of Serbia declared end of measles outbreak after almost 2 years since its start.

Bearing in mind that double maximum incubation period for measles infection has passed, considering that vaccination coverage has been significantly improved in 2018 to 93.4%, and only 15 cases has been reported during 2019, the conditions to declare the end of measles outbreak in the Republic of Serbia have been met.

Since October 2017 when the outbreak started, 5798 cases and 15 fatalities have been reported (CFR: 2.59 per 1000).

The first suspected cases were reported at the beginning of October 2017. The circulation of _Morbillivirus_ in population was laboratory confirmed on [6 Oct 2017] and outbreak declared on [23 Oct 2017]. At that time, total number of laboratory-confirmed cases was 7. Low herd immunity level and high contagiousness of virus led to rapid spread of disease. Vaccine coverage at that time was only 81% in total, while in major cities (Belgrade and Nis) it was below 70%. The first fatality was reported at the end of December 2017 (after a period of 20 years without fatalities from measles).

The peak of the outbreak was reached at the end of [February 2018], together with the majority of fatalities. An intense campaign of the importance of immunization led to improvements in vaccination coverage reaching 93.4% in total (94.3% in central Serbia and 90.9% in Vojvodina). The catch-up campaign resulted in 13 674 children vaccinated with 1st dose of MMR (who missed vaccination by regular immunization calendar) as well as 3233 children vaccinated by 2nd dose and 1452 who got both doses.

In 2019, only 15 cases have been reported of which 4 were imported (from Russia, Ukraine, Austria and North Macedonia). Last reported case was in June 2019.

Based on:
http://www.batut.org.rs/index.php?content=1934
http://www.batut.org.rs/index.php?content=1629
http://morbilli.geonav.xyz/
[in Serbian]

--
Aleksandar Jovicic

[Note the virus is referred to as _Morbillivirus_. Measles _morbillivirus_, formerly called measles virus (MeV), is a single-stranded, negative-sense, enveloped, non-segmented RNA virus of the genus _Morbillivirus_ within the family _Paramyxoviridae_. It is the cause of measles. This is wonderful news and Serbia should be congratulated on its successful campaign against measles. - Mod.LK]

******
[9] Europe update
Date: Thu 4 Sep 2019
Source: EU Policies [abridged, edited]
http://eu-policies.com/news/despite-eu-efforts-measles-cases-still-rise/


Health campaigners have warned that the number of measles cases will continue to rise if vaccination isn't brought back up to previous levels. And in a recent report, the WHO has found the disease has returned in 4 EU countries that had previously eliminated it.

In the UK, Greece, the Czech Republic and Albania, new outbreaks of measles have been blamed on anti-vaccination campaigns on social media. There have also been increases in the number of cases in other states, including Poland and Slovakia.

In a poll carried out by Eurobarometer, 85% of EU citizens believe vaccines are effective in preventing diseases. However, nearly 50% believe they can also cause serious side effects.

Although the EU has been working on increasing awareness and coordination on vaccination programmes, the WHO found that, in the 1st half of 2019, the number of cases had doubled from the previous period - from 44 175 to 89 994.

The group Vaccines Europe believe that this is inaccurate and that vaccines are essential and should be encouraged by the EU.

But some health groups believe that it should be up to individual member states, not the EU, to decide whether vaccination should be mandatory and to develop their own strategies to increase coverage.

In an interview, Dr. Günter Pfaff, chair of the European Regional Verification Commission for Measles and Rubella Elimination said: "Re-establishment of measles transmission is concerning. If high immunisation coverage is not achieved and sustained in every community, both children and adults will suffer unnecessarily and some will tragically die."

Last year [2018], the European Commission proposed that it could strengthen its voluntary cooperation against vaccine-preventable diseases. This was not adopted by the council, but it's been agreed that action needs to be taken to stop "forgotten" diseases returning.

Going forward, Health Commissioner Vytenis Andriukaitis has called for policymakers and health professionals to make sure the public is fully informed in order to boost national vaccination programmes

[Byline: Seth Dervey]

